    "recap_headline": "University of Louisville Athletics",
    "recap_text": "LOUISVILLE, Ky. \u2013\nThe University of Louisville baseball team continued to stay hot at the plate as it turned in an 18-8 victory in seven innings over Marshall on Wednesday morning at Jim Patterson Stadium.\nLouisville (12-5) stretched its winning streak to five with its fourth mercy-rule victory during that period.\nIn the two-game sweep of Marshall, the Cardinals scored 34 runs on 36 hits, blasting eight home runs and 17 total extra-base hits.\nThe two sides traded first inning runs on Wednesday, with\nTague Davis\ngetting the Cards on the board with a run-scoring single.\nMarshall (8-8) would grab the lead back with a run in the second, but it would be the last time the Thundering Herd led on the day.\nGeorge Baker\nknotted the game up at two with a single in the second and Louisville grabbed its first lead of the day on a bases loaded walk to\nLucas Moore\n.\nZion Rose\nwould single home a run to add to the lead before Davis hit an 0-2 pitch onto the berm for Louisville's second grand slam in as many games. The long ball also extended Davis' home run streak to five consecutive games.\nThe Cardinals put a seven-spot on the board in the second inning for the third time in the last five games.\nThe offense didn't slow from there though.\nAlex Alicea\ndoubled in a run in the third before Davis rifled out his second homer of the day, this time a three-run shot.\nOne inning later,\nLucas Moore\ndoubled home Baker and Rose followed with a three-run blast to left for his first homer of the season as the Cardinals led 17-2 after four innings.\nBen Slanker\nlaunched Louisville's fourth homer of the day in the sixth, one day after he homered twice.\nEleven different Cardinals recorded at least one hit on the day, led by three-hit games from Rose, Davis and\nBayram Hot\n. Davis drove in a career-high eight RBIs in the win, matching Slanker's total from Tuesday.\nColton Hartman\n(1-1) was the beneficiary of the offense on Wednesday, picking up the win with two earned runs allowed in five innings.\nLouisville now enters Atlantic Coast Conference play, hosting Notre Dame for three games this weekend. The series begins on Friday at 6 p.m. ET at Jim Patterson Stadium.\nFOLLOW LOUISVILLE BASEBALL ON SOCIAL MEDIA\nFans can follow Louisville baseball on\nX\n,\nFacebook\nor\nInstagram\nat @LouisvilleBSB."
